- Valuations: Mildly bearish. The roll trades at -11c, around \(\sim 4c\) rich vs our estimated fair value, mostly driven by the back contract's richness.

- Optionality: Neutral. The Schatz roll has different CTDs, i.e 1.7% Jun 27 vs 1.9% Sep 27. A switch seems extremely unlikely under any reasonable yield curve scenario. As such net optionality is not a driver of this roll cycle, in our opinion.

- Roll directionality: Neutral. The roll should be directional with the level of yields. Every 10 cents sell off in the front contract should move the roll by \(\sim 1.4\) cents. The roll displays some empirical directionality vs Dec Euribor using the last month of data. While further front-end sell-offs would be bearish for the roll, the modest \(\sim 9\) bp priced into the Dec ECB meeting should limit the downside pressure. Additionally, according to this relationship the current CTD yield spread appears too steep relative to Z5 pricing, although we acknowledge the modest R2 that this relationship depicts.
- Bond RV: Neutral. The 1.7% Jun 27 and the 1.9% Sep 27 do not appear to be misvalued vs an interpolated curve and we do not see much room for relative performance besides directionality.

- Positioning: Bearish. Anecdotal evidence suggests investors remain biased toward steepeners and front-end longs, though in reduced size. Most of the longs appears to have been reduced after President Lagarde's hawkish delivery at the July ECB meeting. Eurex data point to longs on the front contract for \(\sim \epsilon 2.4\) mn/01 whilst the same information is conveyed by looking at the net new longs vs shorts as percentage of total OI. The estimated positioning should exert a bearish pressure into the roll period.

Valuations: Neutral. The roll trades at 102c and it's deemed to be at fair value. Both contracts are trading around \(\sim 2c\) rich vs implied fair value metrics.
Optimality: Neutral. The \(2.6\%\) Aug 34, is the dominant CTD for both contracts. Therefore, net optionality is not a driver of this roll cycle, in our opinion.
Roll directionality and RV: Neutral. As the roll has the same CTD, directionality and RV considerations are negligible for this roll cycle.

Positioning: Mildly Bullish. Duration has traded on the weak side recently. Cash has underperformed swaps with RX ASW leading in the underperformance. As previously mentioned, we believe the bulk of the positioning in Europe is in steepeners. These factors are suggestive of an overall short positioning on RX, whether that is kept in short ASW, steepeners or short outright exposure, which should pose a bullish bias on the roll. Our positioning metrics on the other hand are sending mixed signals, while Eurex is indicating sizable shorts on the front contract, the net longs vs shorts as percentage of OI, computed on a 30dd rolling basis, highlights some recent short covering dynamics, with overall positioning being more neutral.

Valuations: Mildly bullish. The roll trades at 52c, \(\sim 4c\) cheap vs our estimated fair value and mostly driven by the front contract's cheapness.

Optimality: Neutral. The Buxl roll, unlike the previous cycle has the same CTDs, i.e \(2.9\%\) Aug 56. The back contract has some residual optionality value. We estimate a \(\sim 6\%\) probability of a switch in the back contract, with an estimated optionality value worth \(\sim 1c\) . We have 2 competing CTDs in this roll cycle the \(0\%\) Aug 52 and the \(2.5\%\) Aug 54. The Aug 54 would become the new CTD in the case of at least 80bp parallel rally whilst \(\sim 90bp\) parallel sell-off would imply a switch to the Aug 52. Additionally, a flattening of the 56- 54 spread of at least 5bp would allow a CTD switch to the Aug 54. The 56- 54 spread has been trading within a \(\sim 1bp\) range over the last 5 months; hence this scenario would require the curve to reach new lows, which we think is unlikely.
Roll directionality and RV: Neutral. As the roll has the same CTD, directionality and RV considerations are negligible for this roll cycle.

Positioning: Mildly Bullish. Positioning indicators point to some residual short exposure on the front contract, with most of the short exposure being covered towards the end of July. Anecdotally, we believe that steepeners at the long- end part of the curve are still very much in vogue for investors, considering the march higher on the 1030s slope with some long UB ASW exposure offsetting the shorts on the 30y point. Overall, we think the roll should benefit from the overall perceived positioning.

Optionality: Neutral. The BTS roll has two different dominant CTDs, the \(2.7\%\) Oct 27 and the \(2\%\) Feb 28. A switch seems extremely unlikely under any reasonable yield curve scenario. As such net optionality is not a driver of this roll cycle, in our opinion.

Roll directionality: Mildly Bearish. As the roll has different CTDs it is directional with the level of yields. Every 10c move on the front contract should move the roll by \(\sim 1.5c\) . Additionally, the duration neutral CTD spread exhibits some empirical directionality vs the 2s5s slope. Every 10bp of steepening in the curve would flatten the roll by \(\sim 0.01c\) .
RV: Neutral. Both bonds do not appear to be misvalued and we do not see much room for relative performance besides directionality.

Positioning: Bearish. Anecdotal evidence suggests that the market remains generally long Italy. BTS longs are estimated to be worth around \(\sim \epsilon 1.8mn / 01\) on the front- contract from Eurex data, just \(\sim 500mn / 01\) away from max long positioning on the contract over the last 6 months. On the other hand, net longs/shorts as percentage of open interest highlight a divergence signal and point to a fairly neutral positioning on the BTS contract.
